35int static_sign(const Expr &x) {
36 if (is_positive_const(x)) {
37 return 1;
38 } else if (is_negative_const(x)) {
39 return -1;
40 } else {
41 Expr zero = make_zero(x.type());
42 if (equal(const_true(), simplify(x > zero))) {
43 return 1;
44 } else if (equal(const_true(), simplify(x < zero))) {
45 return -1;
46 }
47 }
48 return 0;
49}

57Expr find_constant_bound(const Expr &e, Direction d, const Scope<Interval> &scope) {
58 Interval interval = find_constant_bounds(e, scope);
59 Expr bound;
60 if (interval.has_lower_bound() && (d == Direction::Lower)) {
61 bound = interval.min;
62 } else if (interval.has_upper_bound() && (d == Direction::Upper)) {
63 bound = interval.max;
64 }
65 return bound;
66}
67
68Interval find_constant_bounds(const Expr &e, const Scope<Interval> &scope) {
69 Interval interval = bounds_of_expr_in_scope(e, scope, FuncValueBounds(), true);
70 interval.min = simplify(interval.min);
71 interval.max = simplify(interval.max);
72
73 // Note that we can get non-const but well-defined results (e.g. signed_integer_overflow);
74 // for our purposes here, treat anything non-const as no-bound.
75 if (!is_const(interval.min)) {
76 interval.min = Interval::neg_inf();
77 }
78 if (!is_const(interval.max)) {
79 interval.max = Interval::pos_inf();
80 }
81
82 return interval;
83}

89std::ostream &operator<<(std::ostream &stream, const Box &b) {
90 stream << "{";
91 for (size_t dim = 0; dim < b.size(); dim++) {
92 if (dim > 0) {
93 stream << ", ";
94 }
95 stream << "[" << b[dim].min << ", " << b[dim].max << "]";
96 }
97 stream << "}";
98 if (b.used.defined()) {
99 stream << " if " << b.used;
100 }
101 return stream;
102}

106class Bounds : public IRVisitor {
107public:
108 Interval interval;
109 Scope<Interval> scope;
110 const FuncValueBounds &func_bounds;
111 // If set to true, attempt to return an interval with constant upper
112 // and lower bounds. If the bound is not constant, it is set to
113 // unbounded.
114 bool const_bound;
115
116 Bounds(const Scope<Interval> *s, const FuncValueBounds &fb, bool const_bound)
117 : func_bounds(fb), const_bound(const_bound) {
118 scope.set_containing_scope(s);
119
120 // Find any points that are single_points but fail is_single_point due to
121 // pointer equality checks and replace with single_points.
122 for (auto item = s->cbegin(); item != s->cend(); ++item) {
123 const Interval &item_interval = item.value();
124 if (!item_interval.is_single_point() &&
125 equal(item_interval.min, item_interval.max)) {
126 scope.push(item.name(), Interval::single_point(item_interval.min));
127 }
128 }
129 }

187 // Compute the intrinsic bounds of a function.
188 void bounds_of_func(const string &name, int value_index, Type t) {
189 // if we can't get a good bound from the function, fall back to the bounds of the type.
190 bounds_of_type(t);
191
192 pair<string, int> key = {name, value_index};
193
194 FuncValueBounds::const_iterator iter = func_bounds.find(key);
195
196 if (iter != func_bounds.end()) {
197 if (iter->second.has_lower_bound()) {
198 interval.min = iter->second.min;
199 }
200 if (iter->second.has_upper_bound()) {
201 interval.max = iter->second.max;
202 }
203 }
204 }
205
206 void bounds_of_type(Type t) {
207 t = t.element_of();
208 if ((t.is_uint() || t.is_int()) && t.bits() <= 16) {
209 interval = Interval(t.min(), t.max());
210 } else {
211 interval = Interval::everything();
212 }
213 }

236
237 void visit(const Cast *op) override {
238 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
239 op->value.accept(this);
240 Interval a = interval;
241
242 if (a.is_single_point(op->value)) {
243 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
244 return;
245 }
246
247 Type to = op->type.element_of();
248 Type from = op->value.type().element_of();
249
250 if (a.is_single_point()) {
251 interval = Interval::single_point(Cast::make(to, a.min));
252 return;
253 }
254
255 // If overflow is impossible, cast the min and max. If it's
256 // possible, use the bounds of the destination type.
257 bool could_overflow = true;
258 if (to.can_represent(from) || to.is_float()) {
259 could_overflow = false;
260 } else if (to.is_int() && to.bits() >= 32) {
261 // If we cast to an int32 or greater, assume that it won't
262 // overflow. Signed 32-bit integer overflow is undefined.
263 could_overflow = false;
264 } else if (a.is_bounded()) {
265 if (from.can_represent(to)) {
266 // The other case to consider is narrowing where the
267 // bounds of the original fit into the narrower type. We
268 // can only really prove that this is the case if they're
269 // constants, so try to make the constants first.
270
271 // First constant-fold
272 a.min = simplify(a.min);
273 a.max = simplify(a.max);
274
275 // Then try to strip off junk mins and maxes.
276 bool old_constant_bound = const_bound;
277 const_bound = true;
278 a.min.accept(this);
279 Expr lower_bound = interval.has_lower_bound() ? interval.min : Expr();
280 a.max.accept(this);
281 Expr upper_bound = interval.has_upper_bound() ? interval.max : Expr();
282 const_bound = old_constant_bound;
283
284 if (lower_bound.defined() && upper_bound.defined()) {
285 // Cast them to the narrow type and back and see if
286 // they're provably unchanged.
287 Expr test =
288 (cast(from, cast(to, lower_bound)) == lower_bound &&
289 cast(from, cast(to, upper_bound)) == upper_bound);
290 if (can_prove(test)) {
291 could_overflow = false;
292 // Relax the bounds to the constants we found. Not
293 // strictly necessary, but probably helpful to
294 // keep the expressions small.
295 a = Interval(lower_bound, upper_bound);
296 }
297 }
298 } else {
299 // a is bounded, but from and to can't necessarily represent
300 // each other; however, if the bounds can be simplified to
301 // constants, they might fit regardless of types.
302 a.min = simplify(a.min);
303 a.max = simplify(a.max);
304 const auto *umin = as_const_uint(a.min);
305 const auto *umax = as_const_uint(a.max);
306 if (umin && umax && to.can_represent(*umin) && to.can_represent(*umax)) {
307 could_overflow = false;
308 } else {
309 const auto *imin = as_const_int(a.min);
310 const auto *imax = as_const_int(a.max);
311 if (imin && imax && to.can_represent(*imin) && to.can_represent(*imax)) {
312 could_overflow = false;
313 } else {
314 const auto *fmin = as_const_float(a.min);
315 const auto *fmax = as_const_float(a.max);
316 if (fmin && fmax && to.can_represent(*fmin) && to.can_represent(*fmax)) {
317 could_overflow = false;
318 }
319 }
320 }
321 }
322 }
323
324 if (!could_overflow) {
325 // Start with the bounds of the narrow type.
326 bounds_of_type(from);
327 // If we have a better min or max for the arg use that.
328 if (a.has_lower_bound()) {
329 interval.min = a.min;
330 }
331 if (a.has_upper_bound()) {
332 interval.max = a.max;
333 }
334 // Then cast those bounds to the wider type.
335 if (interval.has_lower_bound()) {
336 interval.min = Cast::make(to, interval.min);
337 }
338 if (interval.has_upper_bound()) {
339 interval.max = Cast::make(to, interval.max);
340 }
341 } else {
342 // This might overflow, so use the bounds of the destination type.
343 bounds_of_type(to);
344 }
345 }
346
347 void visit(const Variable *op) override {
348 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
349 if (const_bound) {
350 bounds_of_type(op->type);
351 if (scope.contains(op->name)) {
352 const Interval &scope_interval = scope.get(op->name);
353 if (scope_interval.has_upper_bound() && is_const(scope_interval.max)) {
354 interval.max = Interval::make_min(interval.max, scope_interval.max);
355 }
356 if (scope_interval.has_lower_bound() && is_const(scope_interval.min)) {
357 interval.min = Interval::make_max(interval.min, scope_interval.min);
358 }
359 }
360
361 if (op->param.defined() &&
362 !op->param.is_buffer() &&
363 (op->param.min_value().defined() ||
364 op->param.max_value().defined())) {
365
366 if (op->param.max_value().defined() && is_const(op->param.max_value())) {
367 interval.max = Interval::make_min(interval.max, op->param.max_value());
368 }
369 if (op->param.min_value().defined() && is_const(op->param.min_value())) {
370 interval.min = Interval::make_max(interval.min, op->param.min_value());
371 }
372 }
373 } else {
374 if (scope.contains(op->name)) {
375 interval = scope.get(op->name);
376 } else if (op->type.is_vector()) {
377 // Uh oh, we need to take the min/max lane of some unknown vector. Treat as unbounded.
378 bounds_of_type(op->type);
379 } else {
380 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
381 }
382 }
383 }

385 void visit(const Add *op) override {
386 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
387 op->a.accept(this);
388 Interval a = interval;
389 op->b.accept(this);
390 Interval b = interval;
391
392 if (a.is_single_point(op->a) && b.is_single_point(op->b)) {
393 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
394 } else if (a.is_single_point() && b.is_single_point()) {
395 interval = Interval::single_point(a.min + b.min);
396 } else {
397 bounds_of_type(op->type);
398 if (a.has_lower_bound() && b.has_lower_bound()) {
399 interval.min = a.min + b.min;
400 }
401 if (a.has_upper_bound() && b.has_upper_bound()) {
402 interval.max = a.max + b.max;
403 }
404
405 // Assume no overflow for float, int32, and int64
406 if (op->type.can_overflow()) {
407 if (!interval.is_bounded()) {
408 // Possibly infinite things that wrap can be anything.
409 bounds_of_type(op->type);
410 return;
411 }
412
413 // TODO(5682): Can't catch overflow of UInt(64) currently.
414 Type t = op->type.is_uint() ? UInt(64) : Int(32);
415 Expr no_overflow_max = (cast(t, a.max) + cast(t, b.max) == cast(t, interval.max));
416 Expr no_overflow_min = (cast(t, a.min) + cast(t, b.min) == cast(t, interval.min));
417 if (!can_prove(no_overflow_max && no_overflow_min)) {
418 bounds_of_type(op->type);
419 return;
420 }
421 }
422 }
423 }

425 void visit(const Sub *op) override {
426 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
427 op->a.accept(this);
428 Interval a = interval;
429 op->b.accept(this);
430 Interval b = interval;
431
432 if (a.is_single_point(op->a) && b.is_single_point(op->b)) {
433 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
434 } else if (a.is_single_point() && b.is_single_point()) {
435 interval = Interval::single_point(a.min - b.min);
436 } else {
437 bounds_of_type(op->type);
438 if (a.has_lower_bound() && b.has_upper_bound()) {
439 interval.min = a.min - b.max;
440 }
441 if (a.has_upper_bound() && b.has_lower_bound()) {
442 interval.max = a.max - b.min;
443 }
444
445 // Assume no overflow for float, int32, and int64
446 if (op->type.can_overflow()) {
447 if (!interval.is_bounded()) {
448 // Possibly infinite things that wrap can be anything.
449 bounds_of_type(op->type);
450 return;
451 }
452
453 Expr no_overflow_max = (cast<int>(a.max) - cast<int>(b.min) == cast<int>(interval.max));
454 Expr no_overflow_min = (cast<int>(a.min) - cast<int>(b.max) == cast<int>(interval.min));
455
456 if (!can_prove(no_overflow_max && no_overflow_min)) {
457 bounds_of_type(op->type);
458 return;
459 }
460 }
461
462 // Check underflow for uint
463 if (op->type.is_uint() &&
464 interval.has_lower_bound() &&
465 !can_prove(b.max <= a.min)) {
466 bounds_of_type(op->type);
467 }
468 }

471 void visit(const Mul *op) override {
472 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
473 op->a.accept(this);
474 Interval a = interval;
475
476 op->b.accept(this);
477 Interval b = interval;
478
479 // Move constants to the right
480 if (a.is_single_point() && !b.is_single_point()) {
481 std::swap(a, b);
482 }
483
484 if (a.is_single_point(op->a) && b.is_single_point(op->b)) {
485 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
486 return;
487 } else if (a.is_single_point() && b.is_single_point()) {
488 interval = Interval::single_point(a.min * b.min);
489 return;
490 } else if (b.is_single_point()) {
491 Expr e1 = a.has_lower_bound() ? a.min * b.min : a.min;
492 Expr e2 = a.has_upper_bound() ? a.max * b.min : a.max;
493 if (is_const_zero(b.min)) {
494 interval = b;
495 } else if (is_positive_const(b.min) || op->type.is_uint()) {
496 interval = Interval(e1, e2);
497 } else if (is_negative_const(b.min)) {
498 if (e1.same_as(Interval::neg_inf())) {
499 e1 = Interval::pos_inf();
500 }
501 if (e2.same_as(Interval::pos_inf())) {
502 e2 = Interval::neg_inf();
503 }
504 interval = Interval(e2, e1);
505 } else if (a.is_bounded()) {
506 // Sign of b is unknown
507 Expr cmp = b.min >= make_zero(b.min.type().element_of());
508 interval = Interval(select(cmp, e1, e2), select(cmp, e2, e1));
509 } else {
510 bounds_of_type(op->type);
511 }
512 } else if (a.is_bounded() && b.is_bounded()) {
513 interval = Interval::nothing();
514 interval.include(a.min * b.min);
515 interval.include(a.min * b.max);
516 interval.include(a.max * b.min);
517 interval.include(a.max * b.max);
518 } else {
519 bounds_of_type(op->type);
520 }
521
522 // Assume no overflow for float, int32, and int64
523 if (op->type.can_overflow()) {
524 if (a.is_bounded() && b.is_bounded()) {
525 // Try to prove it can't overflow. (Be sure to use uint32 for unsigned
526 // types so that the case of 65535*65535 won't misleadingly fail.)
527 // TODO(5682): Can't catch overflow of UInt(64) currently.
528 Type t = op->type.is_uint() ? UInt(64) : Int(32);
529 Expr test1 = (cast(t, a.min) * cast(t, b.min) == cast(t, a.min * b.min));
530 Expr test2 = (cast(t, a.min) * cast(t, b.max) == cast(t, a.min * b.max));
531 Expr test3 = (cast(t, a.max) * cast(t, b.min) == cast(t, a.max * b.min));
532 Expr test4 = (cast(t, a.max) * cast(t, b.max) == cast(t, a.max * b.max));
533 if (!can_prove(test1 && test2 && test3 && test4)) {
534 bounds_of_type(op->type);
535 }
536 } else {
537 bounds_of_type(op->type);
538 }
539 }
540 }
541
542 bool div_cannot_overflow(const Interval &a, const Interval &b, Type t) {
543 // No overflow if: not an allowed overflow int type, or `a` cannot be t.min() or
544 // `b` cannot be -1, because t.min() / -1 overflows for int16 and int8.
545 Expr neg_one = make_const(t, -1);
546 return !t.can_overflow_int() ||
547 (a.has_lower_bound() && can_prove(a.min != t.min())) ||
548 (b.has_upper_bound() && can_prove(b.max < neg_one)) ||
549 (b.has_lower_bound() && can_prove(b.min > neg_one));
550 }
551
552 void visit(const Div *op) override {
553 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
554 op->a.accept(this);
555 Interval a = interval;
556
557 op->b.accept(this);
558 Interval b = interval;
559
560 if (!b.is_bounded()) {
561 // Integer division can only make things smaller in
562 // magnitude (but can flip the sign).
563 if (a.is_bounded() && op->type.is_int() && op->type.bits() >= 32) {
564 // Restrict to no-overflow types to avoid worrying
565 // about overflow due to negating the most negative int.
566 if (can_prove(a.min >= 0)) {
567 interval.min = -a.max;
568 interval.max = a.max;
569 } else if (can_prove(a.max <= 0)) {
570 interval.min = a.min;
571 interval.max = -a.min;
572 } else if (a.is_single_point()) {
573 // The following case would also be correct, but
574 // would duplicate the expression, which is
575 // generally a bad thing for any later interval
576 // arithmetic.
577 interval.min = -cast(a.min.type(), abs(a.min));
578 interval.max = cast(a.min.type(), abs(a.max));
579 } else {
580 // div by 0 is 0 and the magnitude cannot increase by integer division
581 interval.min = min(-a.max, a.min);
582 interval.max = max(-a.min, a.max);
583 }
584 } else {
585 bounds_of_type(op->type);
586 }
587 } else if (a.is_single_point(op->a) && b.is_single_point(op->b)) {
588 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
589 } else if (can_prove(b.min == b.max)) {
590 Expr e1 = a.has_lower_bound() ? a.min / b.min : a.min;
591 Expr e2 = a.has_upper_bound() ? a.max / b.max : a.max;
592
593 Type t = op->type.element_of();
594
595 if (div_cannot_overflow(a, b, t)) {
596 // TODO: handle real numbers with can_prove(b.min > 0) and can_prove(b.min < 0) as well - treating floating point as
597 // reals can be error prone when dealing with division near 0, so for now we only consider integers in the can_prove() path
598 if (op->type.is_uint() || is_positive_const(b.min) || (op->type.is_int() && can_prove(b.min >= 0))) {
599 interval = Interval(e1, e2);
600 } else if (is_negative_const(b.min) || (op->type.is_int() && can_prove(b.min <= 0))) {
601 if (e1.same_as(Interval::neg_inf())) {
602 e1 = Interval::pos_inf();
603 }
604 if (e2.same_as(Interval::pos_inf())) {
605 e2 = Interval::neg_inf();
606 }
607 interval = Interval(e2, e1);
608 } else if (a.is_bounded()) {
609 // Sign of b is unknown.
610 Expr cmp = b.min > make_zero(b.min.type().element_of());
611 interval = Interval(select(cmp, e1, e2), select(cmp, e2, e1));
612 } else {
613 bounds_of_type(op->type);
614 }
615 } else {
616 // Overflow is possible because a can be min value of type t and
617 // b can be -1.
618 bounds_of_type(op->type);
619 }
620 } else if (a.is_bounded()) {
621 // if we can't statically prove that the divisor can't span zero, then we're unbounded
622 int min_sign = static_sign(b.min);
623 int max_sign = static_sign(b.max);
624 if (min_sign != max_sign || min_sign == 0 || max_sign == 0) {
625 if (op->type.is_int() && op->type.bits() >= 32) {
626 // Division can't make signed integers larger
627 // Restricted to 32-bits or greater to ensure the
628 // negation can't overflow.
629 interval = Interval::nothing();
630 interval.include(a.min);
631 interval.include(a.max);
632 interval.include(-a.min);
633 interval.include(-a.max);
634 } else if (op->type.is_uint()) {
635 // Division can't make unsigned integers large,
636 // but could make them arbitrarily small.
637 interval.min = make_zero(a.min.type());
638 interval.max = a.max;
639 } else {
640 // Division can make floats arbitrarily large, and
641 // we can't easily negate narrow bit-width signed
642 // integers because they just wrap.
643 bounds_of_type(op->type);
644 }
645 } else {
646 Type t = op->type.element_of();
647
648 if (div_cannot_overflow(a, b, t)) {
649 // Divisor is either strictly positive or strictly
650 // negative, so we can just take the extrema.
651 interval = Interval::nothing();
652 interval.include(a.min / b.min);
653 interval.include(a.max / b.min);
654 interval.include(a.min / b.max);
655 interval.include(a.max / b.max);
656 } else {
657 // Overflow is possible because a can be min value of type t and
658 // b can be -1.
659 bounds_of_type(op->type);
660 }
661 }
662 } else {
663 bounds_of_type(op->type);
664 }
665 }
666
667 void visit(const Mod *op) override {
668 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
669 op->a.accept(this);
670 Interval a = interval;
671
672 op->b.accept(this);
673 Interval b = interval;
674
675 if (a.is_single_point(op->a) && b.is_single_point(op->b)) {
676 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
677 return;
678 }
679
680 Type t = op->type.element_of();
681
682 // Mod is always positive
683 interval.min = make_zero(t);
684 interval.max = Interval::pos_inf();
685
686 if (!b.is_bounded()) {
687 if (a.has_lower_bound() && can_prove(a.min >= 0)) {
688 // Mod cannot make positive values larger
689 interval.max = a.max;
690 }
691 } else {
692 // b is bounded
693 if (b.max.type().is_int_or_uint() && is_positive_const(b.min)) {
694 // If the RHS is >= 1, the result is in [0, max_b-1]
695 interval.max = b.max - make_one(t);
696 } else if (b.max.type().is_uint()) {
697 // if b.max = 0 then result is [0, 0], else [0, b.max - 1]
698 interval.max = select(b.max == make_zero(t), make_zero(t), b.max - make_one(t));
699 } else if (b.max.type().is_int()) {
700 // x % [4,10] -> [0,9]
701 // x % [-8,-3] -> [0,7]
702 // x % [-8, 10] -> [0,9]
703 interval.max = Max::make(interval.min, b.max - make_one(t));
704 interval.max = Max::make(interval.max, make_const(t, -1) - b.min);
705 } else if (b.max.type().is_float()) {
706 // The floating point version has the same sign rules,
707 // but can reach all the way up to the original value,
708 // so there's no -1.
709 interval.max = Max::make(b.max, -b.min);
710 }
711 }
712 }
713
714 void visit(const Min *op) override {
715 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
716 op->a.accept(this);
717 Interval a = interval;
718
719 op->b.accept(this);
720 Interval b = interval;
721
722 if (a.is_single_point(op->a) && b.is_single_point(op->b)) {
723 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
724 } else {
725 interval = Interval(Interval::make_min(a.min, b.min),
726 Interval::make_min(a.max, b.max));
727 }
728 }

730 void visit(const Max *op) override {
731 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
732 op->a.accept(this);
733 Interval a = interval;
734
735 op->b.accept(this);
736 Interval b = interval;
737
738 if (a.is_single_point(op->a) && b.is_single_point(op->b)) {
739 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
740 } else {
741 interval = Interval(Interval::make_max(a.min, b.min),
742 Interval::make_max(a.max, b.max));
743 }

746 // only used for LT and LE - GT and GE normalize to LT and LTE
747 template<typename Cmp>
748 void visit_compare(const Expr &a_expr, const Expr &b_expr) {
749 a_expr.accept(this);
750 if (!interval.has_upper_bound() && !interval.has_lower_bound()) {
751 bounds_of_type(Bool());
752 return;
753 }
754 Interval a = interval;
755
756 b_expr.accept(this);
757 if (!interval.has_upper_bound() && !interval.has_lower_bound()) {
758 bounds_of_type(Bool());
759 return;
760 }
761 Interval b = interval;
762
763 bounds_of_type(Bool());
764
765 // The returned interval should have the property that min <=
766 // val <= max. For integers it's clear what this means. For
767 // bools, treating false < true, '<=' is in fact
768 // implication. So we want conditions min and max such that
769 // min implies val implies max. So min should be a sufficient
770 // condition, and max should be a necessary condition.
771
772 // a.max <(=) b.min implies a <(=) b, so a <(=) b is at least
773 // as true as a.max <(=) b.min. This does not depend on a's
774 // lower bound or b's upper bound.
775 if (a.has_upper_bound() && b.has_lower_bound()) {
776 interval.min = Cmp::make(a.max, b.min);
777 }
778
779 // a <(=) b implies a.min <(=) b.max, so a <(=) b is at most
780 // as true as a.min <(=) b.max. This does not depend on a's
781 // upper bound or b's lower bound.
782 if (a.has_lower_bound() && b.has_upper_bound()) {
783 interval.max = Cmp::make(a.min, b.max);
784 }
785 }
786
787 void visit(const LT *op) override {
788 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
789 visit_compare<LT>(op->a, op->b);
790 }
791
792 void visit(const LE *op) override {
793 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
794 visit_compare<LE>(op->a, op->b);
795 }
796
797 void visit(const GT *op) override {
798 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
799 visit_compare<LT>(op->b, op->a);
800 }
801
802 void visit(const GE *op) override {
803 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
804 visit_compare<LE>(op->b, op->a);
805 }
806
807 void visit(const EQ *op) override {
808 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
809 op->a.accept(this);
810 Interval a = interval;
811
812 op->b.accept(this);
813 Interval b = interval;
814
815 if (a.is_single_point(op->a) && b.is_single_point(op->b)) {
816 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
817 } else if (a.is_single_point() && b.is_single_point()) {
818 interval = Interval::single_point(a.min == b.min);
819 } else {
820 // If either vary, it could always be false, so we have no
821 // good sufficient condition.
822 bounds_of_type(op->type);
823 // But could it be true? A necessary condition is that the
824 // ranges overlap.
825 if (a.is_bounded() && b.is_bounded()) {
826 interval.max = a.min <= b.max && b.min <= a.max;
827 } else if (a.has_upper_bound() && b.has_lower_bound()) {
828 // a.min <= b.max is implied if a.min = -inf or b.max = +inf.
829 interval.max = b.min <= a.max;
830 } else if (a.has_lower_bound() && b.has_upper_bound()) {
831 // b.min <= a.max is implied if a.max = +inf or b.min = -inf.
832 interval.max = a.min <= b.max;
833 }
834 }
835 }
836
837 void visit(const NE *op) override {
838 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
839 op->a.accept(this);
840 Interval a = interval;
841
842 op->b.accept(this);
843 Interval b = interval;
844
845 if (a.is_single_point(op->a) && b.is_single_point(op->b)) {
846 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
847 } else if (a.is_single_point() && b.is_single_point()) {
848 interval = Interval::single_point(a.min != b.min);
849 } else {
850 // If either vary, it could always be true that they're
851 // not equal, so we have no good necessary condition.
852 bounds_of_type(op->type);
853 // But we do have a sufficient condition. If the ranges of
854 // a and b do not overlap, then they must be not equal.
855 if (a.is_bounded() && b.is_bounded()) {
856 interval.min = a.min > b.max || b.min > a.max;
857 } else if (a.has_upper_bound() && b.has_lower_bound()) {
858 // a.min > b.max is false if a.min = -inf or b.max = +inf.
859 // a does not need a lower bound nor does b need
860 // an upper bound for this condition.
861 interval.min = b.min > a.max;
862 } else if (a.has_lower_bound() && b.has_upper_bound()) {
863 // b.min > a.max is false if a.max = +inf or b.min = -inf.
864 // a does not need an upper bound nor does b need
865 // a lower bound for this condition.
866 interval.min = a.min > b.max;
867 }
868 }
869 }
870
871 Expr make_and(Expr a, Expr b) {
872 if (is_const_one(a)) {
873 return b;
874 }
875 if (is_const_one(b)) {
876 return a;
877 }
878 if (is_const_zero(a)) {
879 return a;
880 }
881 if (is_const_zero(b)) {
882 return b;
883 }
884 return a && b;
885 }
886
887 void visit(const And *op) override {
888 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
889 op->a.accept(this);
890 Interval a = interval;
891
892 op->b.accept(this);
893 Interval b = interval;
894
895 if (a.is_single_point(op->a) && b.is_single_point(op->b)) {
896 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
897 } else if (a.is_single_point() && b.is_single_point()) {
898 interval = Interval::single_point(a.min && b.min);
899 } else {
900 // And is monotonic increasing in both args
901 interval.min = make_and(a.min, b.min);
902 interval.max = make_and(a.max, b.max);
903 }
904 }
905
906 Expr make_or(Expr a, Expr b) {
907 if (is_const_one(a)) {
908 return a;
909 }
910 if (is_const_one(b)) {
911 return b;
912 }
913 if (is_const_zero(a)) {
914 return b;
915 }
916 if (is_const_zero(b)) {
917 return a;
918 }
919 return a || b;
920 }
921
922 void visit(const Or *op) override {
923 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
924 op->a.accept(this);
925 Interval a = interval;
926
927 op->b.accept(this);
928 Interval b = interval;
929
930 if (a.is_single_point(op->a) && b.is_single_point(op->b)) {
931 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
932 } else if (a.is_single_point() && b.is_single_point()) {
933 interval = Interval::single_point(a.min || b.min);
934 } else {
935 // Or is monotonic increasing in both args
936 interval.min = make_or(a.min, b.min);
937 interval.max = make_or(a.max, b.max);
938 }
939 }

941 Expr make_not(const Expr &e) {
942 if (is_const_one(e)) {
943 return make_zero(e.type());
944 }
945 if (is_const_zero(e)) {
946 return make_one(e.type());
947 }
948 return !e;

951 void visit(const Not *op) override {
952 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
953 op->a.accept(this);
954 Interval a = interval;
955
956 if (a.is_single_point(op->a)) {
957 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
958 } else if (a.is_single_point()) {
959 interval = Interval::single_point(!a.min);
960 } else {
961 interval.min = make_not(a.max);
962 interval.max = make_not(a.min);
963 }

965
966 void visit(const Select *op) override {
967 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
968 op->true_value.accept(this);
969 Interval a = interval;
970
971 op->false_value.accept(this);
972 Interval b = interval;
973
974 op->condition.accept(this);
975 Interval cond = interval;
976
977 if (cond.is_single_point()) {
978 if (is_const_one(cond.min)) {
979 interval = a;
980 return;
981 } else if (is_const_zero(cond.min)) {
982 interval = b;
983 return;
984 }
985 }
986
987 Type t = op->type.element_of();
988
989 if (!a.has_lower_bound() || !b.has_lower_bound()) {
990 interval.min = Interval::neg_inf();
991 } else if (a.min.same_as(b.min)) {
992 interval.min = a.min;
993 } else if (cond.is_single_point()) {
994 interval.min = select(cond.min, a.min, b.min);
995 } else if (is_const_zero(cond.min) && is_const_one(cond.max)) {
996 interval.min = Interval::make_min(a.min, b.min);
997 } else if (is_const_one(cond.max)) {
998 // cond.min is non-trivial
999 string var_name = unique_name('t');
1000 Expr var = Variable::make(t, var_name);
1001 interval.min = Interval::make_min(select(cond.min, var, b.min), var);
1002 interval.min = Let::make(var_name, a.min, interval.min);
1003 } else if (is_const_zero(cond.min)) {
1004 // cond.max is non-trivial
1005 string var_name = unique_name('t');
1006 Expr var = Variable::make(t, var_name);
1007 interval.min = Interval::make_min(select(cond.max, a.min, var), var);
1008 interval.min = Let::make(var_name, b.min, interval.min);
1009 } else {
1010 string a_var_name = unique_name('t'), b_var_name = unique_name('t');
1011 Expr a_var = Variable::make(t, a_var_name);
1012 Expr b_var = Variable::make(t, b_var_name);
1013 interval.min = Interval::make_min(select(cond.min, a_var, b_var),
1014 select(cond.max, a_var, b_var));
1015 interval.min = Let::make(a_var_name, a.min, interval.min);
1016 interval.min = Let::make(b_var_name, b.min, interval.min);
1017 }
1018
1019 if (!a.has_upper_bound() || !b.has_upper_bound()) {
1020 interval.max = Interval::pos_inf();
1021 } else if (a.max.same_as(b.max)) {
1022 interval.max = a.max;
1023 } else if (cond.is_single_point()) {
1024 interval.max = select(cond.min, a.max, b.max);
1025 } else if (is_const_zero(cond.min) && is_const_one(cond.max)) {
1026 interval.max = Interval::make_max(a.max, b.max);
1027 } else if (is_const_one(cond.max)) {
1028 // cond.min is non-trivial
1029 string var_name = unique_name('t');
1030 Expr var = Variable::make(t, var_name);
1031 interval.max = Interval::make_max(select(cond.min, var, b.max), var);
1032 interval.max = Let::make(var_name, a.max, interval.max);
1033 } else if (is_const_zero(cond.min)) {
1034 // cond.max is non-trivial
1035 string var_name = unique_name('t');
1036 Expr var = Variable::make(t, var_name);
1037 interval.max = Interval::make_max(select(cond.max, a.max, var), var);
1038 interval.max = Let::make(var_name, b.max, interval.max);
1039 } else {
1040 string a_var_name = unique_name('t'), b_var_name = unique_name('t');
1041 Expr a_var = Variable::make(t, a_var_name);
1042 Expr b_var = Variable::make(t, b_var_name);
1043 interval.max = Interval::make_max(select(cond.min, a_var, b_var),
1044 select(cond.max, a_var, b_var));
1045 interval.max = Let::make(a_var_name, a.max, interval.max);
1046 interval.max = Let::make(b_var_name, b.max, interval.max);
1047 }
1048 }

1050 void visit(const Load *op) override {
1051 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
1052 op->index.accept(this);
1053 if (!const_bound && interval.is_single_point() && is_const_one(op->predicate)) {
1054 // If the index is const and it is not a predicated load,
1055 // we can return the load of that index
1056 Expr load_min =
1057 Load::make(op->type.element_of(), op->name, interval.min,
1058 op->image, op->param, const_true(), ModulusRemainder());
1059 interval = Interval::single_point(load_min);
1060 } else {
1061 // Otherwise use the bounds of the type
1062 bounds_of_type(op->type);
1063 }
1064 }

1066 void visit(const Ramp *op) override {
1067 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
1068 // Treat the ramp lane as a free variable
1069 string var_name = unique_name('t');
1070 Expr var = Variable::make(op->base.type().element_of(), var_name);
1071 Expr lane = op->base + var * op->stride;
1072 Expr min_value = make_const(var.type(), 0);
1073 Expr max_value = make_const(var.type(), op->lanes - 1);
1074 if (!var.type().can_represent((int64_t)(op->lanes - 1))) {
1075 // max_value will overflow.
1076 min_value = var.type().min();
1077 max_value = var.type().max();
1078 }
1079 ScopedBinding<Interval> p(scope, var_name, Interval(min_value, max_value));
1080 lane.accept(this);
1081 }

1083 void visit(const Broadcast *op) override {
1084 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
1085 op->value.accept(this);
1086 }
1087
1088 void visit(const Call *op) override {
1089 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
1090 // Using the strict_float feature flag wraps a strict_float()
1091 // call around every Expr that is of type float, so it's easy
1092 // to get nestings that are many levels deep; the bounds of this
1093 // call are *always* exactly that of its first argument, so short
1094 // circuit it here before checking for const_args. This is important
1095 // because evaluating const_args for such a deeply nested case
1096 // essentially becomes O(n^2) doing work that is unnecessary, making
1097 // otherwise simple pipelines take several minutes to compile.
1098 //
1099 // TODO: are any other intrinsics worth including here as well?
1100 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::strict_float)) {
1101 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 1);
1102 op->args[0].accept(this);
1103 return;
1104 }
1105
1106 Type t = op->type.element_of();
1107
1108 if (t.is_handle()) {
1109 interval = Interval::everything();
1110 return;
1111 }
1112
1113 if (!const_bound &&
1114 (op->call_type == Call::PureExtern ||
1115 op->call_type == Call::Image)) {
1116
1117 // If the args are const we can return the call of those args
1118 // for pure functions. For other types of functions, the same
1119 // call in two different places might produce different
1120 // results (e.g. during the update step of a reduction), so we
1121 // can't move around call nodes.
1122 //
1123 // Note: Only evaluate new_args if we know the call is a candidate;
1124 // otherwise we can get n^2 evaluation time for deeply-nested
1125 // Expr trees.
1126
1127 std::vector<Expr> new_args(op->args.size());
1128 bool const_args = true;
1129 for (size_t i = 0; i < op->args.size() && const_args; i++) {
1130 op->args[i].accept(this);
1131 if (interval.is_single_point()) {
1132 new_args[i] = interval.min;
1133 } else {
1134 const_args = false;
1135 }
1136 }
1137 if (const_args) {
1138 Expr call = Call::make(t, op->name, new_args, op->call_type,
1139 op->func, op->value_index, op->image, op->param);
1140 interval = Interval::single_point(call);
1141 return;
1142 }
1143 // else fall thru and continue
1144 }
1145
1146 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::abs)) {
1147 op->args[0].accept(this);
1148 Interval a = interval;
1149 interval.min = make_zero(t);
1150 if (a.is_bounded()) {
1151 if (equal(a.min, a.max)) {
1152 interval = Interval::single_point(Call::make(t, Call::abs, {a.max}, Call::PureIntrinsic));
1153 } else if (op->args[0].type().is_int() && op->args[0].type().bits() >= 32) {
1154 interval.max = Max::make(Cast::make(t, -a.min), Cast::make(t, a.max));
1155 } else {
1156 a.min = Call::make(t, Call::abs, {a.min}, Call::PureIntrinsic);
1157 a.max = Call::make(t, Call::abs, {a.max}, Call::PureIntrinsic);
1158 interval.max = Max::make(a.min, a.max);
1159 }
1160 } else {
1161 // If the argument is unbounded on one side, then the max is unbounded.
1162 interval.max = Interval::pos_inf();
1163 }
1164 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::absd)) {
1165 internal_assert(!t.is_handle());
1166 if (t.is_float()) {
1167 Expr e = abs(op->args[0] - op->args[1]);
1168 e.accept(this);
1169 } else {
1170 // absd() for int types will always produce a uint result
1171 internal_assert(t.is_uint());
1172
1173 Expr a = op->args[0];
1174 Expr b = op->args[1];
1175 internal_assert(a.type() == b.type());
1176
1177 a.accept(this);
1178 Interval a_interval = interval;
1179
1180 b.accept(this);
1181 Interval b_interval = interval;
1182
1183 if (a_interval.is_bounded() && b_interval.is_bounded()) {
1184 interval.min = make_zero(t);
1185 interval.max = max(absd(a_interval.max, b_interval.min), absd(a_interval.min, b_interval.max));
1186 } else {
1187 bounds_of_type(t);
1188 }
1189 }
1190 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::unsafe_promise_clamped) ||
1191 op->is_intrinsic(Call::promise_clamped)) {
1192 // Unlike an explicit clamp, we are also permitted to
1193 // assume the upper bound is greater than the lower bound.
1194 op->args[1].accept(this);
1195 Interval lower = interval;
1196 op->args[2].accept(this);
1197 Interval upper = interval;
1198 op->args[0].accept(this);
1199
1200 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::promise_clamped) &&
1201 interval.is_single_point()) {
1202 // It's not safe to lift a promise_clamped
1203 // intrinsic. They make a claim that holds true at
1204 // that specific point in the IR. But if it's a single
1205 // point we're probably inside the scope over which
1206 // the thing varies, so we don't want to needlessly
1207 // complicate the IR by injecting the min/max. For now
1208 // we just drop the annotation and return the bounds
1209 // of the first arg.
1210 return;
1211 }
1212
1213 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::unsafe_promise_clamped) &&
1214 interval.is_single_point(op->args[0]) &&
1215 lower.is_single_point(op->args[1]) &&
1216 upper.is_single_point(op->args[2])) {
1217 // It *is* safe to lift an
1218 // unsafe_promise_clamped. Those are injected by the
1219 // user and represent a promise that holds globally
1220 // across the entire program. So in the case that
1221 // nothing varies we return the full Expr, not just
1222 // the first arg. In the case where things are varying
1223 // we resolve to min/max (i.e. we exploit the promise).
1224 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
1225 return;
1226 }
1227
1228 interval.min = Interval::make_max(interval.min, lower.min);
1229 interval.max = Interval::make_min(interval.max, upper.max);
1230 } else if (Call::as_tag(op)) {
1231 op->args[0].accept(this);
1232 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::return_second)) {
1233 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 2);
1234 op->args[1].accept(this);
1235 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::if_then_else)) {
1236 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 3);
1237 // Probably more conservative than necessary
1238 Expr equivalent_select = Select::make(op->args[0], op->args[1], op->args[2]);
1239 equivalent_select.accept(this);
1240 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::require)) {
1241 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 3);
1242 op->args[1].accept(this);
1243 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::shift_left) ||
1244 op->is_intrinsic(Call::shift_right) ||
1245 op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_xor) ||
1246 op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_and) ||
1247 op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_or)) {
1248 Expr a = op->args[0], b = op->args[1];
1249 a.accept(this);
1250 Interval a_interval = interval;
1251 b.accept(this);
1252 Interval b_interval = interval;
1253 if (a_interval.is_single_point(a) && b_interval.is_single_point(b)) {
1254 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
1255 } else if (a_interval.is_single_point() && b_interval.is_single_point()) {
1256 interval = Interval::single_point(Call::make(t, op->name, {a_interval.min, b_interval.min}, op->call_type));
1257 } else {
1258 bounds_of_type(t);
1259 // For some of these intrinsics applied to integer
1260 // types we can go a little further.
1261 if (t.is_int() || t.is_uint()) {
1262 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::shift_left)) {
1263 if (t.is_int() && t.bits() >= 32) {
1264 // Overflow is UB
1265 if (a_interval.has_lower_bound() &&
1266 b_interval.has_lower_bound() &&
1267 can_prove(b_interval.min >= 0 &&
1268 b_interval.min < t.bits())) {
1269 interval.min = a_interval.min << b_interval.min;
1270 } else if (a_interval.has_lower_bound() &&
1271 b_interval.has_lower_bound() &&
1272 !b_interval.min.type().is_uint() &&
1273 (a_interval.min.type().is_uint() ||
1274 can_prove(a_interval.min >= 0)) &&
1275 can_prove(b_interval.min < 0 &&
1276 b_interval.min > -t.bits())) {
1277 interval.min = a_interval.min >> abs(b_interval.min);
1278 } else if (a_interval.has_lower_bound() &&
1279 a_interval.min.type().is_int() &&
1280 can_prove(a_interval.min < 0) &&
1281 b_interval.has_upper_bound()) {
1282 // If a can be negative, then we split a_interval into
1283 // two ranges, [a.min, 0) and [0, a.max]. Note that the
1284 // second range may not exist, if a's range is fully
1285 // negative, but that doesn't matter - a positive value
1286 // cannot be shifted to produce a negative, so the min
1287 // of the operation is produced in the negative range.
1288 if (!b_interval.max.type().is_uint() &&
1289 can_prove(b_interval.max <= 0)) {
1290 // If b is strictly non-positive, then the magnitude can only decrease.
1291 interval.min = a_interval.min;
1292 } else {
1293 // If b could be positive, then the magnitude might increase.
1294 interval.min = min(a_interval.min, a_interval.min << b_interval.max);
1295 }
1296 } else if (a_interval.has_lower_bound() &&
1297 (a_interval.min.type().is_uint() ||
1298 can_prove(a_interval.min >= 0))) {
1299 // A positive value shifted cannot change sign.
1300 interval.min = make_zero(t);
1301 }
1302 // TODO: Are there any other cases we can handle for interval.min?
1303
1304 if (a_interval.has_upper_bound() &&
1305 b_interval.has_upper_bound() &&
1306 can_prove(b_interval.max >= 0 &&
1307 b_interval.max < t.bits())) {
1308 interval.max = a_interval.max << b_interval.max;
1309 } else if (a_interval.has_upper_bound() &&
1310 b_interval.has_upper_bound() &&
1311 !b_interval.max.type().is_uint() &&
1312 can_prove(b_interval.max < 0 &&
1313 b_interval.max > -t.bits())) {
1314 interval.max = a_interval.max >> abs(b_interval.max);
1315 }
1316 } else if (is_const(b)) {
1317 // We can normalize to multiplication
1318 Expr equiv = a * (make_const(t, 1) << b);
1319 equiv.accept(this);
1320 }
1321 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::shift_right)) {
1322 // Only try to improve on bounds-of-type if we can prove 0 <= b < t.bits,
1323 // as shift_right(a, b) is UB for b outside that range.
1324 if (b_interval.is_bounded()) {
1325 bool b_min_ok_positive = can_prove(b_interval.min >= 0 &&
1326 b_interval.min < t.bits());
1327 bool b_max_ok_positive = can_prove(b_interval.max >= 0 &&
1328 b_interval.max < t.bits());
1329 bool b_min_ok_negative =
1330 !b_interval.min.type().is_uint() &&
1331 can_prove(b_interval.min < 0 && b_interval.min > -t.bits());
1332 bool b_max_ok_negative =
1333 !b_interval.max.type().is_uint() &&
1334 can_prove(b_interval.max < 0 && b_interval.max > -t.bits());
1335 if (a_interval.has_lower_bound()) {
1336 if (b_max_ok_positive && (a_interval.min.type().is_uint() ||
1337 can_prove(a_interval.min >= 0))) {
1338 interval.min = a_interval.min >> b_interval.max;
1339 } else if (can_prove(a_interval.min < 0) && b_max_ok_negative) {
1340 interval.min = a_interval.min << abs(b_interval.max);
1341 } else if (b_min_ok_positive && b_max_ok_positive) {
1342 // if a < 0, the smallest value will be a >> b.min
1343 // if a > 0, the smallest value will be a >> b.max
1344 interval.min = min(a_interval.min >> b_interval.min,
1345 a_interval.min >> b_interval.max);
1346 } else if (b_min_ok_negative && b_max_ok_negative) {
1347 // if a < 0, the smallest value will be a << abs(b.min)
1348 // if a > 0, the smallest value will be a << abs(b.max)
1349 interval.min = min(a_interval.min << abs(b_interval.min),
1350 a_interval.min << abs(b_interval.max));
1351 }
1352 }
1353 if (a_interval.has_upper_bound()) {
1354 if (can_prove(a_interval.max >= 0) && b_min_ok_positive) {
1355 interval.max = a_interval.max >> b_interval.min;
1356 } else if (can_prove(a_interval.max < 0) && b_min_ok_negative) {
1357 interval.max = a_interval.max << abs(b_interval.min);
1358 } else if (b_min_ok_positive && b_max_ok_positive) {
1359 // if a < 0, the largest value will be a >> b.max
1360 // if a > 0, the largest value will be a >> b.min
1361 interval.max = max(a_interval.max >> b_interval.max,
1362 a_interval.max >> b_interval.min);
1363 } else if (b_min_ok_negative && b_max_ok_negative) {
1364 // if a < 0, the largest value will be a << abs(b.max)
1365 // if a > 0, the largest value will be a << abs(b.min)
1366 interval.max = max(a_interval.max << abs(b_interval.max),
1367 a_interval.max << abs(b_interval.min));
1368 }
1369 }
1370 }
1371 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_and) &&
1372 a_interval.has_upper_bound() &&
1373 b_interval.has_upper_bound()) {
1374 bool a_positive = a_interval.has_lower_bound() && can_prove(a_interval.min >= 0);
1375 bool b_positive = b_interval.has_lower_bound() && can_prove(b_interval.min >= 0);
1376 if (a_positive && b_positive) {
1377 // Positive and smaller than both args
1378 interval.max = min(a_interval.max, b_interval.max);
1379 interval.min = make_zero(t);
1380 } else if (t.is_int()) {
1381 if (b_positive) {
1382 interval.min = make_zero(t);
1383 interval.max = b_interval.max;
1384 } else if (a_positive) {
1385 interval.min = make_zero(t);
1386 interval.max = a_interval.max;
1387 } else {
1388 // Smaller than the larger of the two args
1389 interval.max = max(a_interval.max, b_interval.max);
1390 }
1391 }
1392
1393 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_or) &&
1394 a_interval.has_lower_bound() &&
1395 b_interval.has_lower_bound()) {
1396 if (t.is_int()) {
1397 // Larger than the smaller arg
1398 interval.min = min(a_interval.min, b_interval.min);
1399 } else if (t.is_uint()) {
1400 // Larger than both args
1401 interval.min = max(a_interval.min, b_interval.min);
1402 }
1403 }
1404 }
1405 }
1406 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::bitwise_not)) {
1407 // In 2's complement bitwise not inverts the ordering of
1408 // the space, without causing overflow (unlike negation),
1409 // so bitwise not is monotonic decreasing.
1410 op->args[0].accept(this);
1411 Interval a_interval = interval;
1412 if (a_interval.is_single_point(op->args[0])) {
1413 interval = Interval::single_point(op);
1414 } else if (a_interval.is_single_point()) {
1415 interval = Interval::single_point(~a_interval.min);
1416 } else {
1417 bounds_of_type(t);
1418 if (t.is_int() || t.is_uint()) {
1419 if (a_interval.has_upper_bound()) {
1420 interval.min = ~a_interval.max;
1421 }
1422 if (a_interval.has_lower_bound()) {
1423 interval.max = ~a_interval.min;
1424 }
1425 }
1426 }
1427 } else if (op->args.size() == 1 && interval.is_bounded() &&
1428 (op->name == "ceil_f32" || op->name == "ceil_f64" ||
1429 op->name == "floor_f32" || op->name == "floor_f64" ||
1430 op->name == "round_f32" || op->name == "round_f64" ||
1431 op->name == "exp_f32" || op->name == "exp_f64" ||
1432 op->name == "log_f32" || op->name == "log_f64")) {
1433 // For monotonic, pure, single-argument functions, we can
1434 // make two calls for the min and the max.
1435 interval = Interval(
1436 Call::make(t, op->name, {interval.min}, op->call_type,
1437 op->func, op->value_index, op->image, op->param),
1438 Call::make(t, op->name, {interval.max}, op->call_type,
1439 op->func, op->value_index, op->image, op->param));
1440 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::popcount) ||
1441 op->is_intrinsic(Call::count_leading_zeros) ||
1442 op->is_intrinsic(Call::count_trailing_zeros)) {
1443 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 1);
1444 const Type &t = op->type.element_of();
1445 Expr min = make_zero(t);
1446 Expr max = make_const(t, op->args[0].type().bits());
1447 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::count_leading_zeros)) {
1448 // clz treats signed and unsigned ints the same way;
1449 // cast all ints to uint to simplify this.
1450 cast(op->type.with_code(halide_type_uint), op->args[0]).accept(this);
1451 Interval a = interval;
1452 if (a.has_lower_bound()) {
1453 max = cast(t, count_leading_zeros(a.min));
1454 }
1455 if (a.has_upper_bound()) {
1456 min = cast(t, count_leading_zeros(a.max));
1457 }
1458 }
1459 interval = Interval(min, max);
1460 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::memoize_expr)) {
1461 internal_assert(!op->args.empty());
1462 op->args[0].accept(this);
1463 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::scatter_gather)) {
1464 // Take the union of the args
1465 Interval result = Interval::nothing();
1466 for (const Expr &e : op->args) {
1467 e.accept(this);
1468 result.include(interval);
1469 }
1470 interval = result;
1471 } else if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::mux)) {
1472 // Take the union of all args but the first
1473 Interval result = Interval::nothing();
1474 for (size_t i = 1; i < op->args.size(); i++) {
1475 op->args[i].accept(this);
1476 result.include(interval);
1477 }
1478 interval = result;
1479 } else if (op->call_type == Call::Halide) {
1480 bounds_of_func(op->name, op->value_index, op->type);
1481 } else {
1482 // Just use the bounds of the type
1483 bounds_of_type(t);
1484 }
1485 }
1486
1487 void visit(const Let *op) override {
1488 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
1489 op->value.accept(this);
1490 Interval val = interval;
1491
1492 // We'll either substitute the values in directly, or pass
1493 // them in as variables and add an outer let (to avoid
1494 // combinatorial explosion).
1495 Interval var;
1496 string min_name = op->name + ".min";
1497 string max_name = op->name + ".max";
1498
1499 if (val.has_lower_bound()) {
1500 if (is_const(val.min)) {
1501 // Substitute it in
1502 var.min = val.min;
1503 val.min = Expr();
1504 } else {
1505 var.min = Variable::make(op->value.type().element_of(), min_name);
1506 }
1507 }
1508
1509 if (val.has_upper_bound()) {
1510 if (is_const(val.max)) {
1511 // Substitute it in
1512 var.max = val.max;
1513 val.max = Expr();
1514 } else if (val.is_single_point()) {
1515 var.max = var.min;
1516 } else {
1517 var.max = Variable::make(op->value.type().element_of(), max_name);
1518 }
1519 }
1520
1521 {
1522 ScopedBinding<Interval> p(scope, op->name, var);
1523 op->body.accept(this);
1524 }
1525
1526 bool single_point = interval.is_single_point();
1527
1528 if (interval.has_lower_bound()) {
1529 if (val.min.defined() &&
1530 expr_uses_var(interval.min, min_name)) {
1531 interval.min = Let::make(min_name, val.min, interval.min);
1532 }
1533 if (val.max.defined() &&
1534 !val.is_single_point() &&
1535 expr_uses_var(interval.min, max_name)) {
1536 interval.min = Let::make(max_name, val.max, interval.min);
1537 }
1538 }
1539
1540 if (single_point) {
1541 interval.max = interval.min;
1542 } else if (interval.has_upper_bound()) {
1543 if (val.min.defined() &&
1544 expr_uses_var(interval.max, min_name)) {
1545 interval.max = Let::make(min_name, val.min, interval.max);
1546 }
1547 if (val.max.defined() &&
1548 !val.is_single_point() &&
1549 expr_uses_var(interval.max, max_name)) {
1550 interval.max = Let::make(max_name, val.max, interval.max);
1551 }
1552 }
1553 }
1554
1555 void visit(const Shuffle *op) override {
1556 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
1557 Interval result = Interval::nothing();
1558 for (const Expr &i : op->vectors) {
1559 i.accept(this);
1560 result.include(interval);
1561 }
1562 interval = result;
1563 }
1564
1565 void visit(const VectorReduce *op) override {
1566 TRACK_BOUNDS_INTERVAL;
1567 op->value.accept(this);
1568 int factor = op->value.type().lanes() / op->type.lanes();
1569 switch (op->op) {
1570 case VectorReduce::Add:
1571 if (interval.has_upper_bound()) {
1572 interval.max *= factor;
1573 }
1574 if (interval.has_lower_bound()) {
1575 interval.min *= factor;
1576 }
1577 break;
1578 case VectorReduce::SaturatingAdd:
1579 case VectorReduce::Mul:
1580 // Technically there are some things we could say
1581 // here. E.g. if all the lanes are positive then we're
1582 // bounded by the upper bound raised to the factor
1583 // power. However it's extremely unlikely that a mul
1584 // reduce will ever make it into a bounds expression, so
1585 // for now we bail.
1586 bounds_of_type(op->value.type());
1587 break;
1588 case VectorReduce::Min:
1589 case VectorReduce::Max:
1590 case VectorReduce::And:
1591 case VectorReduce::Or:
1592 // The bounds of a single lane are sufficient
1593 break;
1594 }
1595 }

1636Interval bounds_of_expr_in_scope(const Expr &expr, const Scope<Interval> &scope, const FuncValueBounds &fb, bool const_bound) {
1637 //debug(3) << "computing bounds_of_expr_in_scope " << expr << "\n";
1638 Bounds b(&scope, fb, const_bound);
1639 expr.accept(&b);
1640 //debug(3) << "bounds_of_expr_in_scope " << expr << " = " << simplify(b.interval.min) << ", " << simplify(b.interval.max) << "\n";
1641 Type expected = expr.type().element_of();
1642 if (b.interval.has_lower_bound()) {
1643 internal_assert(b.interval.min.type() == expected)
1644 << "Min of " << expr
1645 << " should have been a scalar of type " << expected
1646 << ": " << b.interval.min << "\n";
1647 }
1648 if (b.interval.has_upper_bound()) {
1649 internal_assert(b.interval.max.type() == expected)
1650 << "Max of " << expr
1651 << " should have been a scalar of type " << expected
1652 << ": " << b.interval.max << "\n";
1653 }
1654 return b.interval;
1655}
1656
1657Region region_union(const Region &a, const Region &b) {
1658 internal_assert(a.size() == b.size()) << "Mismatched dimensionality in region union\n";
1659 Region result;
1660 for (size_t i = 0; i < a.size(); i++) {
1661 Expr min = Min::make(a[i].min, b[i].min);
1662 Expr max_a = a[i].min + a[i].extent;
1663 Expr max_b = b[i].min + b[i].extent;
1664 Expr max_plus_one = Max::make(max_a, max_b);
1665 Expr extent = max_plus_one - min;
1666 result.push_back(Range(simplify(min), simplify(extent)));
1667 //result.push_back(Range(min, extent));
1668 }
1669 return result;
1670}
1671
1672void merge_boxes(Box &a, const Box &b) {
1673 if (b.empty()) {
1674 return;
1675 }
1676
1677 if (a.empty()) {
1678 a = b;
1679 return;
1680 }
1681
1682 internal_assert(a.size() == b.size());
1683
1684 bool a_maybe_unused = a.maybe_unused();
1685 bool b_maybe_unused = b.maybe_unused();
1686
1687 bool complementary = a_maybe_unused && b_maybe_unused &&
1688 (equal(a.used, !b.used) || equal(!a.used, b.used));
1689
1690 for (size_t i = 0; i < a.size(); i++) {
1691 if (!a[i].min.same_as(b[i].min)) {
1692 if (a[i].has_lower_bound() && b[i].has_lower_bound()) {
1693 if (a_maybe_unused && b_maybe_unused) {
1694 if (complementary) {
1695 a[i].min = select(a.used, a[i].min, b[i].min);
1696 } else {
1697 a[i].min = select(a.used && b.used, Interval::make_min(a[i].min, b[i].min),
1698 a.used, a[i].min,
1699 b[i].min);
1700 }
1701 } else if (a_maybe_unused) {
1702 a[i].min = select(a.used, Interval::make_min(a[i].min, b[i].min), b[i].min);
1703 } else if (b_maybe_unused) {
1704 a[i].min = select(b.used, Interval::make_min(a[i].min, b[i].min), a[i].min);
1705 } else {
1706 a[i].min = Interval::make_min(a[i].min, b[i].min);
1707 }
1708 a[i].min = simplify(a[i].min);
1709 } else {
1710 a[i].min = Interval::neg_inf();
1711 }
1712 }
1713 if (!a[i].max.same_as(b[i].max)) {
1714 if (a[i].has_upper_bound() && b[i].has_upper_bound()) {
1715 if (a_maybe_unused && b_maybe_unused) {
1716 if (complementary) {
1717 a[i].max = select(a.used, a[i].max, b[i].max);
1718 } else {
1719 a[i].max = select(a.used && b.used, Interval::make_max(a[i].max, b[i].max),
1720 a.used, a[i].max,
1721 b[i].max);
1722 }
1723 } else if (a_maybe_unused) {
1724 a[i].max = select(a.used, Interval::make_max(a[i].max, b[i].max), b[i].max);
1725 } else if (b_maybe_unused) {
1726 a[i].max = select(b.used, Interval::make_max(a[i].max, b[i].max), a[i].max);
1727 } else {
1728 a[i].max = Interval::make_max(a[i].max, b[i].max);
1729 }
1730 a[i].max = simplify(a[i].max);
1731 } else {
1732 a[i].max = Interval::pos_inf();
1733 }
1734 }
1735 }
1736
1737 if (a_maybe_unused && b_maybe_unused) {
1738 if (!equal(a.used, b.used)) {
1739 a.used = simplify(a.used || b.used);
1740 if (is_const_one(a.used)) {
1741 a.used = Expr();
1742 }
1743 }
1744 } else {
1745 a.used = Expr();
1746 }
1747}
1748
1749Box box_union(const Box &a, const Box &b) {
1750 Box result = a;
1751 merge_boxes(result, b);
1752 return result;
1753}
1754
1755Box box_intersection(const Box &a, const Box &b) {
1756 Box result;
1757 if (a.empty() || b.empty()) {
1758 return result;
1759 }
1760
1761 internal_assert(a.size() == b.size());
1762 result.resize(a.size());
1763
1764 for (size_t i = 0; i < a.size(); i++) {
1765 result[i].min = simplify(max(a[i].min, b[i].min));
1766 result[i].max = simplify(min(a[i].max, b[i].max));
1767 }
1768
1769 // The intersection is only used if both a and b are used.
1770 if (a.maybe_unused() && b.maybe_unused()) {
1771 result.used = a.used && b.used;
1772 } else if (a.maybe_unused()) {
1773 result.used = a.used;
1774 } else if (b.maybe_unused()) {
1775 result.used = b.used;
1776 }
1777
1778 return result;
1779}
1780
1781bool boxes_overlap(const Box &a, const Box &b) {
1782 // If one box is scalar and the other is not, the boxes cannot
1783 // overlap.
1784 if (a.size() != b.size() && (a.empty() || b.empty())) {
1785 return false;
1786 }
1787
1788 internal_assert(a.size() == b.size());
1789
1790 bool a_maybe_unused = a.maybe_unused();
1791 bool b_maybe_unused = b.maybe_unused();
1792
1793 // Overlapping requires both boxes to be used.
1794 Expr overlap = ((a_maybe_unused ? a.used : const_true()) &&
1795 (b_maybe_unused ? b.used : const_true()));
1796
1797 for (size_t i = 0; i < a.size(); i++) {
1798 if (a[i].has_upper_bound() && b[i].has_lower_bound()) {
1799 overlap = overlap && b[i].max >= a[i].min;
1800 }
1801 if (a[i].has_lower_bound() && b[i].has_upper_bound()) {
1802 overlap = overlap && a[i].max >= b[i].min;
1803 }
1804 }
1805
1806 // Conservatively, assume they overlap if we can't prove there's no overlap
1807 return !can_prove(simplify(!overlap));
1808}
1809
1810bool box_contains(const Box &outer, const Box &inner) {
1811 // If the inner box has more dimensions than the outer box, the
1812 // inner box cannot fit in the outer box.
1813 if (inner.size() > outer.size()) {
1814 return false;
1815 }
1816 Expr condition = const_true();
1817 for (size_t i = 0; i < inner.size(); i++) {
1818 if ((outer[i].has_lower_bound() && !inner[i].has_lower_bound()) ||
1819 (outer[i].has_upper_bound() && !inner[i].has_upper_bound())) {
1820 return false;
1821 }
1822 if (outer[i].has_lower_bound()) {
1823 condition = condition && (outer[i].min <= inner[i].min);
1824 }
1825 if (outer[i].has_upper_bound()) {
1826 condition = condition && (outer[i].max >= inner[i].max);
1827 }
1828 }
1829 if (outer.maybe_unused()) {
1830 if (inner.maybe_unused()) {
1831 // inner condition must imply outer one
1832 condition = condition && ((outer.used && inner.used) == inner.used);
1833 } else {
1834 // outer box is conditional, but inner is not
1835 return false;
1836 }
1837 }
1838 return can_prove(condition);
1839}

1867// Place innermost vars in an IfThenElse's condition as far to the left as possible.
1868class SolveIfThenElse : public IRMutator {
1869 // Scope of variable names and their depths. Higher depth indicates
1870 // variable defined more innermost.
1871 Scope<int> vars_depth;
1872 int depth = -1;
1873
1874 using IRMutator::visit;
1875
1876 void push_var(const string &var) {
1877 depth += 1;
1878 vars_depth.push(var, depth);
1879 }
1880
1881 void pop_var(const string &var) {
1882 depth -= 1;
1883 vars_depth.pop(var);
1884 }
1885
1886 Stmt visit(const LetStmt *op) override {
1887 push_var(op->name);
1888 Stmt stmt = IRMutator::visit(op);
1889 pop_var(op->name);
1890 return stmt;
1891 }
1892
1893 Stmt visit(const For *op) override {
1894 push_var(op->name);
1895 Stmt stmt = IRMutator::visit(op);
1896 pop_var(op->name);
1897 return stmt;
1898 }
1899
1900 Stmt visit(const IfThenElse *op) override {
1901 Stmt stmt = IRMutator::visit(op);
1902 op = stmt.as<IfThenElse>();
1903 internal_assert(op);
1904
1905 FindInnermostVar find(vars_depth);
1906 op->condition.accept(&find);
1907 if (!find.innermost_var.empty()) {
1908 Expr condition = solve_expression(op->condition, find.innermost_var).result;
1909 if (!condition.same_as(op->condition)) {
1910 stmt = IfThenElse::make(condition, op->then_case, op->else_case);
1911 }
1912 }
1913 return stmt;
1914 }

1938// Compute the box produced by a statement
1939class BoxesTouched : public IRGraphVisitor {
1940
1941public:
1942 BoxesTouched(bool calls, bool provides, string fn, const Scope<Interval> *s, const FuncValueBounds &fb)
1943 : func(std::move(fn)), consider_calls(calls), consider_provides(provides), func_bounds(fb) {
1944 scope.set_containing_scope(s);
1945 }
1946
1947 map<string, Box> boxes;
1948
1949private:
1950 struct VarInstance {
1951 string var;
1952 int instance;
1953 VarInstance(const string &v, int i)
1954 : var(v), instance(i) {
1955 }
1956 VarInstance() = default;
1957
1958 bool operator==(const VarInstance &other) const {
1959 return (var == other.var) && (instance == other.instance);
1960 }
1961 bool operator<(const VarInstance &other) const {
1962 if (var == other.var) {
1963 return (instance < other.instance);
1964 }
1965 return (var < other.var);
1966 }
1967 };
1968
1969 string func;
1970 bool consider_calls, consider_provides;
1971 Scope<Interval> scope;
1972 const FuncValueBounds &func_bounds;
1973 // Scope containing the current value definition of let stmts.
1974 Scope<Expr> let_stmts;
1975 // Keep track of variable renaming. Map variable name to instantiation number
1976 // (0 for the first variable to be defined, 1 for the 1st redefinition, etc.).
1977 map<string, int> vars_renaming;
1978 // Map variable name to all other vars which values depend on that variable.
1979 map<VarInstance, set<VarInstance>> children;
1980
1981 bool in_producer{false};
1982 map<std::string, Expr> buffer_lets;
1983
1984 using IRGraphVisitor::visit;
1985
1986 bool box_from_extended_crop(const Expr &e, Box &b) {
1987 const Call *call_expr = e.as<Call>();
1988 if (call_expr != nullptr) {
1989 if (call_expr->name == Call::buffer_crop) {
1990 internal_assert(call_expr->args.size() == 5)
1991 << "Call::buffer_crop call with unexpected number of arguments.\n";
1992 const Variable *in_buf = call_expr->args[2].as<Variable>();
1993 const Call *mins_struct = call_expr->args[3].as<Call>();
1994 const Call *extents_struct = call_expr->args[4].as<Call>();
1995 // Ignore crops that apply to a different buffer than the one being looked for.
1996 if (in_buf != nullptr && (in_buf->name == (func + ".buffer"))) {
1997 internal_assert(mins_struct != nullptr && extents_struct != nullptr &&
1998 mins_struct->is_intrinsic(Call::make_struct) &&
1999 extents_struct->is_intrinsic(Call::make_struct))
2000 << "BoxesTouched::box_from_extended_crop -- unexpected buffer_crop form.\n";
2001 b.resize(mins_struct->args.size());
2002 b.used = const_true();
2003 for (size_t i = 0; i < mins_struct->args.size(); i++) {
2004 Interval min_interval = bounds_of_expr_in_scope(mins_struct->args[i], scope, func_bounds);
2005 Interval max_interval = bounds_of_expr_in_scope(mins_struct->args[i] + extents_struct->args[i] - 1, scope, func_bounds);
2006 b[i] = Interval(min_interval.min, max_interval.max);
2007 }
2008 return true;
2009 }
2010 } else if (call_expr->name == Call::buffer_set_bounds) {
2011 internal_assert(call_expr->args.size() == 4)
2012 << "Call::buffer_set_bounds call with unexpected number of arguments.\n";
2013 const IntImm *dim = call_expr->args[1].as<IntImm>();
2014 if (dim != nullptr && box_from_extended_crop(call_expr->args[0], b)) {
2015 internal_assert(dim->value >= 0 && dim->value < (int64_t)b.size())
2016 << "box_from_extended_crop setting bounds for out of range dim.\n";
2017 Interval min_interval = bounds_of_expr_in_scope(call_expr->args[2], scope, func_bounds);
2018 Interval max_interval = bounds_of_expr_in_scope(call_expr->args[2] + call_expr->args[3] - 1, scope, func_bounds);
2019 b[dim->value] = Interval(min_interval.min, max_interval.max);
2020 return true;
2021 }
2022 }
2023 }
2024 return false;
2025 }
2026
2027 void visit(const Call *op) override {
2028 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::declare_box_touched)) {
2029 internal_assert(!op->args.empty());
2030 const Variable *handle = op->args[0].as<Variable>();
2031 const string &func = handle->name;
2032 Box b(op->args.size() / 2);
2033 for (size_t i = 0; i < b.size(); i++) {
2034 b[i].min = op->args[2 * i + 1];
2035 b[i].max = op->args[2 * i + 2];
2036 }
2037 merge_boxes(boxes[func], b);
2038 }
2039
2040 if (consider_calls) {
2041 if (op->is_intrinsic(Call::if_then_else)) {
2042 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 3);
2043 // We wrap 'then_case' and 'else_case' inside 'dummy' call since IfThenElse
2044 // only takes Stmts as arguments.
2045 Stmt then_case = Evaluate::make(op->args[1]);
2046 Stmt else_case = Evaluate::make(op->args[2]);
2047 Stmt equivalent_if = IfThenElse::make(op->args[0], then_case, else_case);
2048 equivalent_if.accept(this);
2049 return;
2050 }
2051
2052 IRGraphVisitor::visit(op);
2053
2054 if (op->call_type == Call::Halide ||
2055 op->call_type == Call::Image) {
2056 for (const Expr &e : op->args) {
2057 e.accept(this);
2058 }
2059 if (op->name == func || func.empty()) {
2060 Box b(op->args.size());
2061 b.used = const_true();
2062 for (size_t i = 0; i < op->args.size(); i++) {
2063 b[i] = bounds_of_expr_in_scope(op->args[i], scope, func_bounds);
2064 }
2065 merge_boxes(boxes[op->name], b);
2066 }
2067 }
2068 }
2069
2070 if (op->is_extern() && (in_producer || consider_calls)) {
2071 if (op->name == "halide_buffer_copy") {
2072 // Call doesn't yet have user_context inserted, so size is 3.
2073 internal_assert(op->args.size() == 3) << "Unexpected arg list size for halide_buffer_copy\n";
2074 for (int i = 0; i < 2; i++) {
2075 // If considering calls, merge in the source bounds.
2076 // If considering provides, merge in the destination bounds.
2077 int var_index;
2078 if (i == 0 && consider_calls) {
2079 var_index = 0;
2080 } else if (i == 1 && consider_provides && in_producer) {
2081 var_index = 2;
2082 } else {
2083 continue;
2084 }
2085
2086 const Variable *var = op->args[var_index].as<Variable>();
2087 if (var != nullptr && var->type == type_of<halide_buffer_t *>()) {
2088 if (func.empty() || starts_with(var->name, func)) {
2089 const auto iter = buffer_lets.find(var->name);
2090 if (iter != buffer_lets.end()) {
2091 Box b;
2092 if (box_from_extended_crop(iter->second, b)) {
2093 merge_boxes(boxes[func], b);
2094 }
2095 }
2096 }
2097 }
2098 }
2099 }
2100 }
2101 }

2103 class CountVars : public IRVisitor {
2104 using IRVisitor::visit;
2105
2106 void visit(const Variable *var) override {
2107 count++;
2108 }
2109
2110 public:
2111 int count = 0;
2112 CountVars() = default;
2113 };
2114
2115 // We get better simplification if we directly substitute mins
2116 // and maxes in, but this can also cause combinatorial code
2117 // explosion. Here we manage this by only substituting in
2118 // reasonably-sized expressions. We determine the size by
2119 // counting the number of var nodes.
2120 bool is_small_enough_to_substitute(const Expr &e) {
2121 CountVars c;
2122 e.accept(&c);
2123 return c.count < 10;
2124 }
2125
2126 void push_var(const string &name) {
2127 auto iter = vars_renaming.find(name);
2128 if (iter == vars_renaming.end()) {
2129 vars_renaming.emplace(name, 0);
2130 } else {
2131 iter->second += 1;
2132 }
2133 }
2134
2135 void pop_var(const string &name) {
2136 auto iter = vars_renaming.find(name);
2137 internal_assert(iter != vars_renaming.end());
2138 iter->second -= 1;
2139 if (iter->second < 0) {
2140 vars_renaming.erase(iter);
2141 }
2142 }
2143
2144 VarInstance get_var_instance(const string &name) {
2145 // It is possible for the variable to be not in 'vars_renaming', e.g.
2146 // the output buffer min/max. In this case, we just add the variable
2147 // to the renaming map and assign it to instance 0.
2148 return VarInstance(name, vars_renaming[name]);
2149 }
2150
2151 template<typename LetOrLetStmt>
2152 void visit_let(const LetOrLetStmt *op) {
2153 using is_let_stmt = typename std::is_same<LetOrLetStmt, LetStmt>;
2154
2155 // LetStmts can be deeply stacked, and this visitor is called
2156 // before dead lets are eliminated, so we move all the
2157 // internal state off the call stack into an explicit stack on
2158 // the heap.
2159 struct Frame {
2160 set<string> old_let_vars;
2161 const LetOrLetStmt *op;
2162 VarInstance vi;
2163 CollectVars collect;
2164 string max_name, min_name;
2165 Interval value_bounds;
2166 Frame(const LetOrLetStmt *op)
2167 : op(op), collect(op->name) {
2168 }
2169 };
2170
2171 vector<Frame> frames;
2172 decltype(op->body) result;
2173 while (op) {
2174 frames.emplace_back(op);
2175 Frame &f = frames.back();
2176 push_var(op->name);
2177
2178 if (op->value.type() == type_of<struct halide_buffer_t *>()) {
2179 buffer_lets[op->name] = op->value;
2180 }
2181
2182 if (is_let_stmt::value) {
2183 f.vi = get_var_instance(op->name);
2184
2185 // Update the 'children' map.
2186 op->value.accept(&f.collect);
2187 for (const auto &v : f.collect.vars) {
2188 children[get_var_instance(v)].insert(f.vi);
2189 }
2190
2191 // If this let stmt is a redefinition of a previous one, we should
2192 // remove the old let stmt from the 'children' map since it is
2193 // no longer valid at this point.
2194 if ((f.vi.instance > 0) && let_stmts.contains(op->name)) {
2195 const Expr &val = let_stmts.get(op->name);
2196 CollectVars collect(op->name);
2197 val.accept(&collect);
2198 f.old_let_vars = collect.vars;
2199
2200 VarInstance old_vi = VarInstance(f.vi.var, f.vi.instance - 1);
2201 for (const auto &v : f.old_let_vars) {
2202 internal_assert(vars_renaming.count(v));
2203 children[get_var_instance(v)].erase(old_vi);
2204 }
2205 }
2206 let_stmts.push(op->name, op->value);
2207 }
2208
2209 op->value.accept(this);
2210
2211 f.value_bounds = bounds_of_expr_in_scope(op->value, scope, func_bounds);
2212
2213 bool fixed = f.value_bounds.min.same_as(f.value_bounds.max);
2214 f.value_bounds.min = simplify(f.value_bounds.min);
2215 f.value_bounds.max = fixed ? f.value_bounds.min : simplify(f.value_bounds.max);
2216
2217 if (is_small_enough_to_substitute(f.value_bounds.min) &&
2218 (fixed || is_small_enough_to_substitute(f.value_bounds.max))) {
2219 scope.push(op->name, f.value_bounds);
2220 } else {
2221 f.max_name = unique_name('t');
2222 f.min_name = unique_name('t');
2223 scope.push(op->name, Interval(Variable::make(op->value.type(), f.min_name),
2224 Variable::make(op->value.type(), f.max_name)));
2225 }
2226
2227 result = op->body;
2228 op = result.template as<LetOrLetStmt>();
2229 }
2230
2231 result.accept(this);
2232
2233 for (auto it = frames.rbegin(); it != frames.rend(); it++) {
2234 // Pop the value bounds
2235 scope.pop(it->op->name);
2236
2237 if (it->op->value.type() == type_of<struct halide_buffer_t *>()) {
2238 buffer_lets.erase(it->op->name);
2239 }
2240
2241 if (!it->min_name.empty()) {
2242 // We made up new names for the bounds of the
2243 // value, and need to rewrap any boxes we're
2244 // returning with appropriate lets.
2245 for (pair<const string, Box> &i : boxes) {
2246 Box &box = i.second;
2247 for (size_t i = 0; i < box.size(); i++) {
2248 if (box[i].has_lower_bound()) {
2249 if (expr_uses_var(box[i].min, it->max_name)) {
2250 box[i].min = Let::make(it->max_name, it->value_bounds.max, box[i].min);
2251 }
2252 if (expr_uses_var(box[i].min, it->min_name)) {
2253 box[i].min = Let::make(it->min_name, it->value_bounds.min, box[i].min);
2254 }
2255 }
2256 if (box[i].has_upper_bound()) {
2257 if (expr_uses_var(box[i].max, it->max_name)) {
2258 box[i].max = Let::make(it->max_name, it->value_bounds.max, box[i].max);
2259 }
2260 if (expr_uses_var(box[i].max, it->min_name)) {
2261 box[i].max = Let::make(it->min_name, it->value_bounds.min, box[i].max);
2262 }
2263 }
2264 }
2265 }
2266 }
2267
2268 if (is_let_stmt::value) {
2269 let_stmts.pop(it->op->name);
2270
2271 // If this let stmt shadowed an outer one, we need
2272 // to re-insert the children from the previous let
2273 // stmt into the map.
2274 if (!it->old_let_vars.empty()) {
2275 internal_assert(it->vi.instance > 0);
2276 VarInstance old_vi = VarInstance(it->vi.var, it->vi.instance - 1);
2277 for (const auto &v : it->old_let_vars) {
2278 internal_assert(vars_renaming.count(v));
2279 children[get_var_instance(v)].insert(old_vi);
2280 }
2281 }
2282
2283 // Remove the children from the current let stmt.
2284 for (const auto &v : it->collect.vars) {
2285 internal_assert(vars_renaming.count(v));
2286 children[get_var_instance(v)].erase(it->vi);
2287 }
2288 }
2289
2290 pop_var(it->op->name);
2291 }
2292 }

2294 void visit(const Let *op) override {
2295 visit_let(op);
2296 }
2297
2298 void visit(const LetStmt *op) override {
2299 visit_let(op);
